    "43462129": {
      "title": "Bad groups of finite Morley rank",
      "abstract": "We prove the following theorem. Let G be a connected simple bad group (i.e. of finite Morley rank, nonsolvable and with all the Borel subgroups nilpotent) of minimal Morley rank. Then the Borel subgroups of G are conjugate to each other, and if B is a Borel subgroup of G, then G = UgeGB9, NG(B) = B, and G has no involutions. ?0. Introduction. The following conjecture is well known. CHERLIN CONJECTURE. Every simple co-stable group of finite Morley rank is an algebraic group over an algebraically closed field. In Proposition 1 we will show that if this is true, then the following conjecture should also be true. (*) There are no connected co-stable groups of finite Morley rank with all Borel subgroups (i.e. the maximal definable connected solvable subgroups of G) proper and nilpotent. In Proposition 1 we show that if there is a counterexample to (*), we can suppose it to be simple. But there is no such situation for algebraic groups over an algebraically closed field (see [Hu, ?21.4, Proposition B]). We call a counterexample to (*) a bad group, and we will show that a bad group with minimal Morley rank, which can supposed to be simple, has most of the structure properties which were shown by Cherlin and Nesin for the \"bad groups of Morley rank 3\" in [Ch] and [N2]. More exactly, what we show in this article is thefollowing. THEOREM 1. Let G be a bad group, simple and of minimal Morley rank. Then: (1) [ZIL'BER]. If B and S are different Borel subgroups of G, then B rn S = (1). (2) The Borel subgroups of G are conjugate to each other. (3) G = UgeG B9, where B is a Borel subgroup of G. (4) NG(B) = B, where B is a Borel subgroup of G and NG(B) the normalizer of B in G. (5) G has no involutions. Received July 7, 1987; revised February 23, 1988. 'The results in this article were obtained in February and March 1987 and will be a part of my Doctoral thesis under the supervision of Professor M. Ziegler at the University of Bonn. I would like to thank him for his valuable help and guidance during my studies. I would like to thank also Professor G. Cherlin for some important talks we had during the summer of 1986. I would like to express my gratitude to the Deutscher Akademischer Austauschdienst for their financial support in the form of a scholarship. ? 1989, Association for Symbolic Logic 0022-4812/89/5403-0008/$01.60"
    }
